root.geography: Spoken in the northern half of the island of Halmahera, off the western extremity of Irian Jaya, the Bird's Head Penninsula in western Irian Jaya,
root.pub-comments: West Papuan, though it has been included in the Trans-New Guinea phylum by many scholars in the past, is not anymore. Many languages have been moved out of the West Papuan phylum into Trans-New Guinea, but the two are in fact distinctly separate.

Klabra is regarded as a language, different from Tehit, by Voorhoeve (1975a) and Flassy and Stokhof (1979). However, the latter include Khlabra dialect under Tehit, stating at the same time that the village listing for it is incomplete. This suggests the presence of a dialect chain between Tehit and Kalabra (Klabra), with the Khlabra dialect of Tehit, and intermediate dialect between the two languages. Speakers: 2000?
